a very nice Indiana Deer Legal High Powered Rifle of which only a hand full are available.

I have a custom built Remington Model 700 That was a 350 Remington Magnum
it has been shortened to 1.8 inch. Indiana Deer Legal casing
the factory barrel has been bedded and set back to shorten the chamber.
It comes with Redding Dies that have been ground to match. 
I have brass and about 30rds of ammo that was made by C F Gunworks.
It is toped off with a leupold 3x9.
This rifle killed 3 deer at over 300yds this past season. It is amazing!!
I would like $1800 with scope or $1600 without.

This Rifle was custom built to Indiana Specs!!!!! And is referred to as a 350 JR
 This cartridge is modeled after the Remington 350 Magnum. They shorten the case
 to 1.8 inches, I took a picture so you can see the cartridge, bullet is 200grn
and clearly meets Indiana guide lines. I hope this helps with the confusion. 
Certain rifles like the .357 magnum or .44 magnum can be bought at walmart

title: For Sale:  BUFFALO BORE AMMO - DEER GRENADE .44 MAGNUM +P AMMO - 240 GR.SOFT CAST - G.C. (1,550 FPS) - 20 ROUND BOX
postcontent:
http://extreme-impact-ammo.com/index.php?l=product_detail&p=232

Buffalo Bore's Deer Grenade 44 Mag. +P is a 240gr. Massive, Hollow Nosed, 12 BHN cast bullet with a gas check traveling at the below velocities out of stock, real world, over-the-counter firearms:

1. 1935 fps -- Marlin 1894 20 inch

2. 1897 fps -- Marlin 1894 18 inch

3. 1871 fps -- Marlin 1894 16.5 inch

4. 1578 fps -- Ruger Super Blackhawk 5.5 inch

5. 1535 fps -- Ruger Redhawk 5.5 inch

6. 1466 fps -- S&W MT Gun 4 inch

This load is designed as the world's premier deer load for 44 mag. The cast bullet is not considered soft, but it is not really a HARD cast bullet either as it only has a BHN (Brinell Hardness Numnber) of 12 so, it could be termed a medium/hard cast bullet. It performs as follows:

At an impact velocity of 1,100 fps it will mushroom to about 75 Cal. and should push right through any deer with a broadside shot.

At an impact velocity of 1,500 fps it will mushroom and some of the mushroom will fragment off and send bullet particles flying through the deer, but much of the mushroom and shank will remain intact and should push through any deer hit broadside.

At an impact velocity of 1,900 fps the entire mushroom will turn into shrapnel and send bullet particles all throughout the deer. The shank will remain intact, but will re-mushroom and do horrific damage inside the deer and will probably push through any deer hit broadside.

Of course all these results will vary depending on how much bone, if any, you hit, etc. This load was designed specifically to do horrific damage to deer sized game and as such does not penetrate like a hard cast flat nosed bullet. This bullet only penetrates about 30% as deep as a typical flat nosed hard cast bullet, which is perfect penetration for shallow game like deer, and medium sized pigs or black bear. This load is your best bet for immediately anchoring any deer with the 44 mag. cartridge that is not CNS (central nervous system) hit.

This bullet is properly alloyed, lubed and is gas checked; it will NOT lead-foul barrels.

This load is designed to be safe in ALL/ANY, all steel firearms that are in normal operating condition. We do not recommend its use in lightweight alloyed revolvers as the bullets may jump the crimp.

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rock River Arms PDS Carbine
postcontent:
Thinking of parting with my RRA PDS carbine. Setup as it now stands includes:
1) RRA Tri rail system, new cost $170
2) forward grip
3) diamond head flip up BUIS 
4) Trijicon ACOG 
5) premium stock with additional space for storage

Typically the rifle without these additions retails for about $1600-1700 when you can find them. Since the Rock River piston system doesn't require a buffer tube the entire stock is now available for storage. For example if you have a small Tac light you can put that where the buffer would have been, throw in a couple of extra batteries and keep them with you while keeping your AR as streamlined as possible until you need that light, or laser or whatnot. Maybe the coolest part is that the absence of the buffer lets the stock fold. The RRA folding system doesn't interfere with charging or firing the gun in either position, locks solidly and deploys quickly. It also has a 2 position gas block so that if you're in a field situation, as round count and fouling increase, you can change to HIGH to allow more gas to drive the piston. This keeps you firing when standard gas op ARs may have failed. There are a lot of cool features to this AR, and Rock River is an excellent manufacturer. Since I can't stand folks who say "I don't need to sell, just seeing what's out there" I'll try to be more specific. I'm interested in cash, precious metals, and other quality firearms. Sig 226 family in 9mm, lever action .22s, and other quality ARs get preference, but all will be considered.  Not all of the accessories listed have to go with the rifle (except the Tri Rail of course) so let me know what you have to offer and what you want and we can try to make a deal. Mags and Ammo are a possibility if needed. Thanks for reading. Pics on request. All offers get a response.
